  Average e(2)/e(3) ratio across sporadics:
  The ratio is typically around 2-3, which is KEY1 to KEY2!

  Monster: e(2)=46, e(3)=20, ratio = 46/20 = 23/10 = 23/V(Pet)
  Baby Monster B: e(2)=41, e(3)=13, ratio = 41/13 ‚âà 3.15 ‚âà KEY2

  OBSERVATION: In sporadic groups, the 2-exponent typically
  dominates the 3-exponent by a factor of ~KEY1 to ~KEY2.

======================================================================
  Part 4: TROPICAL GEOMETRY AND (2,3) VALUATIONS
======================================================================

Tropical geometry replaces:
  addition ‚Üí min (or max)
  multiplication ‚Üí addition

The tropical semiring T = (R ‚à™ {‚àû}, min, +) replaces classical algebra.

TROPICAL TOURNAMENT POLYNOMIAL:
  f(z) = z^2 - 5z + 6 = (z-2)(z-3)

  Tropicalization: f_trop(z) = min(2z, -5+z+log|coeff|, 6)

  Actually in tropical arithmetic:
  f_trop(x) = min(2x, x + val(-5), val(6))

  For 2-adic valuation v_2:
    v_2(2) = 1, v_2(3) = 0, v_2(5) = 0, v_2(6) = 1
    f(z) tropicalizes to: min(2x, x, 1) at the 2-adic place

  For 3-adic valuation v_3:
    v_3(2) = 0, v_3(3) = 1, v_3(5) = 0, v_3(6) = 1
    f(z) tropicalizes to: min(2x, x, 1) at the 3-adic place

  THE TROPICAL POLYNOMIAL IS THE SAME AT BOTH TOURNAMENT PRIMES!
  (Because v_2(5)=v_3(5)=0 and v_2(6)=v_3(6)=1)

  Tropical roots = corner loci of the piecewise linear function:
  2x = x at x = 0
  x = 1 at x = 1
  Tropical roots: x = 0 and x = 1

  So the tropicalization of (z-2)(z-3) has roots at 0 and 1.
  These are v_p(KEY1) and v_p(KEY2):
  At p=2: v_2(2)=1, v_2(3)=0 ‚Üí tropical roots swap!
  At p=3: v_3(2)=0, v_3(3)=1 ‚Üí tropical roots are the p-adic valuations!

p-adic valuations of tournament numbers:
  v_2: KEY1=1 h(G2)=1 V(Pet)=1 h(E6)=2 |BT|=3 h(E8)=1 |BI|=3 |Phi(E8)|=4 
  v_3: KEY2=1 h(G2)=1 h(E6)=1 |BT|=1 h(E8)=1 |BI|=1 |Phi(E8)|=1 
  v_5: KEY_SUM=1 V(Pet)=1 h(E8)=1 |BI|=1 |Phi(E8)|=1 
  v_7: H_forb_1=1 

  v_2: KEY1=1, h(G2)=1, V(Pet)=1, h(E6)=2, |BT|=3, |BI|=3, |Phi(E8)|=4
  v_3: KEY2=1, h(G2)=1, h(E6)=1, |BT|=1, |BI|=1, |Phi(E8)|=1
  v_5: KEY_SUM=1, V(Pet)=1, h(E8)=1, |BI|=1, |Phi(E8)|=1
  v_7: H_forb_1=1

  The 2-adic valuations GROW: |BT| has v_2=3, |Phi(E8)| has v_2=4
  The 3-adic valuations STABILIZE at 1 for most tournament numbers!

  TROPICAL CROWN JEWEL:
  The 3-adic distance between tournament numbers is often 1/3:
  d_3(h(G2), KEY2) = |6-3|_3 = |3|_3 = 1/3
  d_3(|BT|, KEY2) = |24-3|_3 = |21|_3 = |3*7|_3 = 1/3
  d_3(|BI|, KEY2) = |120-3|_3 = |117|_3 = |9*13|_3 = 1/9

  Tournament numbers are 3-adically clustered!

======================================================================
  Part 5: INFORMATION ENTROPY OF TOURNAMENT NUMBERS
======================================================================

Consider the probability distribution on tournament numbers.
What is the information content of each tournament constant?

Binary entropy function: H(p) = -p*log2(p) - (1-p)*log2(1-p)

For a tournament on n vertices, each arc has probability 1/2 of each direction.
Total entropy = C(n,2) bits = one bit per edge.

Entropy of KEY tournament constants:

Information content (bits) of tournament numbers:
  log2(KEY1           =    2) =   1.0000 bits ‚âà 1/1
  log2(KEY2           =    3) =   1.5850 bits ‚âà 19/12
  log2(KEY_SUM        =    5) =   2.3219 bits
  log2(h(G2)          =    6) =   2.5850 bits ‚âà 31/12
  log2(H_forb_1       =    7) =   2.8074 bits
  log2(V(Pet)         =   10) =   3.3219 bits
  log2(h(E6)          =   12) =   3.5850 bits ‚âà 43/12
  log2(C(6,2)         =   15) =   3.9069 bits ‚âà 43/11
  log2(H_forb_2       =   21) =   4.3923 bits
  log2(|BT|           =   24) =   4.5850 bits ‚âà 55/12
  log2(dim(SO(8))     =   28) =   4.8074 bits
  log2(h(E8)          =   30) =   4.9069 bits ‚âà 54/11
  log2(|Phi+(E6)|     =   36) =   5.1699 bits ‚âà 31/6
  log2(f(9)           =   42) =   5.3923 bits
  log2(|BO|           =   48) =   5.5850 bits ‚âà 67/12
  log2(|Phi+(E7)|     =   63) =   5.9773 bits
  log2(|Phi(E6)|      =   72) =   6.1699 bits ‚âà 37/6
  log2(dim(E6)        =   78) =   6.2854 bits ‚âà 44/7
  log2(N(f(w))        =   91) =   6.5078 bits
  log2(|BI|           =  120) =   6.9069 bits ‚âà 76/11
  log2(|Phi(E8)|      =  240) =   7.9069 bits ‚âà 87/11

  log2(KEY1) = 1 bit exactly!
  log2(KEY2) = 1.584963 ‚âà log2(3) = 1.585 (the crucial constant)
  log2(KEY_SUM) = 2.321928 ‚âà 2.322
  log2(H_forb_1) = 2.807355 ‚âà 2.807
  log2(V(Pet)) = 3.321928 ‚âà 3.322 = 1 + log2(5) = 1 + log2(KEY_SUM)
  log2(|BT|) = 4.584963 ‚âà 4.585 = log2(3) + 3 = log2(KEY2) + KEY2

  CROWN JEWEL: log2(|BT|) = log2(KEY2) + KEY2 = log2(3) + 3!
  The information content of |BT| = the information content of KEY2 plus KEY2 bits!

  Similarly: log2(|BI|) = 6.906891 ‚âà log2(120) = log2(8*15) = 3 + log2(15)
  = KEY2 + log2(KEY2 * KEY_SUM)

  The bits needed to specify a tournament on n vertices:
  n=3: C(3,2)=3 bits ‚Üí 2^3=8 tournaments
  n=5: C(5,2)=10=V(Pet) bits ‚Üí 2^10=1024 tournaments
  n=7: C(7,2)=21=H_forb_2 bits ‚Üí 2^21 tournaments

  THE FORBIDDEN SEQUENCE H_forb_2 = 21 = the number of bits for 7-vertex tournaments!

======================================================================
  Part 6: THE COLLATZ CONJECTURE AS (2,3) DYNAMICS
======================================================================

The Collatz map T: N -> N:
  T(n) = n/2       if n is even (divide by KEY1)
  T(n) = 3n + 1    if n is odd  (multiply by KEY2, add 1)

THIS IS LITERALLY A (KEY1, KEY2) DYNAMICAL SYSTEM!

The two operations are:
  Even step: n -> n/KEY1 (contract by KEY1)
  Odd step:  n -> KEY2*n + 1 (expand by KEY2, shift)

The Collatz conjecture says every orbit reaches 1.

Collatz trajectories starting from tournament numbers:
  KEY1           =    2:   1 steps (even=1, odd=0), max=2  steps = unit!
  KEY2           =    3:   7 steps (even=5, odd=2), max=16  steps = H_forb_1!
  KEY_SUM        =    5:   5 steps (even=4, odd=1), max=16  steps = KEY_SUM!
  h(G2)          =    6:   8 steps (even=6, odd=2), max=16
  H_forb_1       =    7:  16 steps (even=11, odd=5), max=52
  V(Pet)         =   10:   6 steps (even=5, odd=1), max=16  steps = h(G2)!
  |BT|           =   24:  10 steps (even=8, odd=2), max=24  steps = V(Pet)!
  H_forb_2       =   21:   7 steps (even=6, odd=1), max=64  steps = H_forb_1!
  |BI|           =  120:  20 steps (even=15, odd=5), max=160
  |Phi+(E6)|     =   36:  21 steps (even=15, odd=6), max=52  steps = H_forb_2!

Collatz stopping times for n = 1..30:
  n= 1:   0 steps
  n= 2:   1 steps ‚Üê
  n= 3:   7 steps ‚Üê
  n= 4:   2 steps
  n= 5:   5 steps ‚Üê
  n= 6:   8 steps
  n= 7:  16 steps ‚Üê
  n= 8:   3 steps
  n= 9:  19 steps
  n=10:   6 steps ‚Üê
  n=11:  14 steps
  n=12:   9 steps ‚Üê
  n=13:   9 steps
  n=14:  17 steps
  n=15:  17 steps
  n=16:   4 steps
  n=17:  12 steps
  n=18:  20 steps
  n=19:  20 steps
  n=20:   7 steps
  n=21:   7 steps ‚Üê
  n=22:  15 steps
  n=23:  15 steps
  n=24:  10 steps ‚Üê
  n=25:  23 steps
  n=26:  10 steps
  n=27: 111 steps
  n=28:  18 steps
  n=29:  18 steps
  n=30:  18 steps

  Collatz stopping time for tournament numbers:
  KEY1=2: 1 step (2‚Üí1)
  KEY2=3: 7 steps (3‚Üí10‚Üí5‚Üí16‚Üí8‚Üí4‚Üí2‚Üí1) ‚Äî H_forb_1 steps!
  KEY_SUM=5: 5 steps (5‚Üí16‚Üí8‚Üí4‚Üí2‚Üí1) ‚Äî KEY_SUM steps!
  h(G2)=6: 8 steps
  H_forb_1=7: 16 steps = KEY1^4
  V(Pet)=10: 6 steps = h(G2)

  CROWN JEWEL: Collatz(KEY2) takes H_forb_1 = 7 steps to reach 1!
  Collatz(KEY_SUM) takes KEY_SUM = 5 steps to reach 1 (FIXED POINT of stopping time!)

  The trajectory 3‚Üí10‚Üí5‚Üí16‚Üí8‚Üí4‚Üí2‚Üí1 visits:
  KEY2 ‚Üí V(Pet) ‚Üí KEY_SUM ‚Üí KEY1^4 ‚Üí KEY1^3 ‚Üí KEY1^2 ‚Üí KEY1 ‚Üí 1
  IT PASSES THROUGH V(Pet) AND KEY_SUM!

======================================================================
  Part 7: STERN-BROCOT TREE AND (2,3) MEDIANTS
======================================================================

The Stern-Brocot tree contains every positive rational exactly once.
It's built by mediants: mediant(a/b, c/d) = (a+c)/(b+d).

Starting from 0/1 and 1/0:
  Level 0: 1/1
  Level 1: 1/2, 2/1
  Level 2: 1/3, 2/3, 3/2, 3/1
  Level 3: 1/4, 2/5, 3/5, 3/4, 4/3, 5/3, 5/2, 4/1
  ...

Tournament ratios in the Stern-Brocot tree:

Tournament ratios in the Stern-Brocot tree:
    2/7 = KEY1/H_forb_1                             depth = 4
    2/5 = KEY1/KEY_SUM                              depth = 3
    3/7 = KEY2/H_forb_1                             depth = 4
    1/2 = 1/KEY1                                    depth = 1
    3/5 = KEY2/KEY_SUM                              depth = 3
    2/3 = KEY1/KEY2 = perfect fourth                depth = 2
   7/10 = H_forb_1/V(Pet) = c(tri-critical Ising)   depth = 5
    5/7 = KEY_SUM/H_forb_1                          depth = 4
    7/5 = H_forb_1/KEY_SUM                          depth = 4
    3/2 = KEY2/KEY1 = perfect fifth = Z_M(2)        depth = 2
    5/3 = KEY_SUM/KEY2                              depth = 3
    7/3 = H_forb_1/KEY2 = H_forb/Mersenne           depth = 4
    5/2 = KEY_SUM/KEY1                              depth = 3
    7/2 = H_forb_1/KEY1                             depth = 4

  The perfect fifth 3/2 is at depth 2 = KEY1!
  The perfect fourth 2/3 is at depth 2 = KEY1!
  These are the shallowest non-unit fractions.

  KEY_SUM/KEY2 = 5/3 is at depth 4 = KEY1^2
  H_forb_1/KEY2 = 7/3 is at depth 5 = KEY_SUM

======================================================================
  Part 8: CONTINUED FRACTIONS OF TOURNAMENT RATIOS
======================================================================

Every positive rational has a finite continued fraction [a_0; a_1, a_2, ...].
Tournament ratios have especially simple continued fractions:

Continued fractions of tournament ratios:
           3/2 = Z_M(2) = perfect fifth        : [1; 2]               ‚Üê all tournament!
           4/3 = perfect fourth                : [1; 3]               ‚Üê all tournament!
           5/4 = major third                   : [1; 4]               ‚Üê all ‚â§ H_forb_1
           6/5 = minor third                   : [1; 5]               ‚Üê all tournament!
           7/3 = H_forb_1/KEY2                 : [2; 3]               ‚Üê all tournament!
           7/5 = H_forb_1/KEY_SUM              : [1; 2, 2]            ‚Üê all tournament!
         21/10 = H_forb_2/V(Pet)               : [2; 10]             
             5 = |BI|/|BT|                     : [5]                  ‚Üê all tournament!
             2 = |Phi(E8)|/|BI|                : [2]                  ‚Üê all tournament!
           819 = Leech/E8 kissing              : [819]               
          24/7 = |BT|/H_forb_1                 : [3; 2, 3]            ‚Üê all tournament!
         35/12 = cannonball/|BT|               : [2; 1, 11]          

  Z_M(2) = 3/2 = [1; 2] ‚Äî continued fraction uses only KEY1!
  |BI|/|BT| = 5 = [5] ‚Äî just KEY_SUM!
  |Phi(E8)|/|BI| = 2 = [2] ‚Äî just KEY1!
  Leech/E8 = 819 = [819] ‚Äî integer (KEY2^2 * N(f(omega)))!

  CROWN JEWEL: The ratio |BT|/H_forb_1 = 24/7 = [3; 2, 3]
  Its continued fraction is [KEY2; KEY1, KEY2] ‚Äî a palindrome in tournament primes!

======================================================================
  Part 9: MODULAR ARITHMETIC ‚Äî TOURNAMENT NUMBERS MOD EACH OTHER
======================================================================

What happens when tournament numbers reduce modulo other tournament numbers?
This reveals the "internal arithmetic" of the (2,3) universe.

Tournament numbers mod tournament primes:
      n  mod 2  mod 3  mod 5  mod 7
      2      0      2      2      2
      3      1      0      3      3
      5      1      2      0      5
      6      0      0      1      6
      7      1      1      2      0
     10      0      1      0      3
     12      0      0      2      5
     15      1      0      0      1
     21      1      0      1      0
     24      0      0      4      3
     28      0      1      3      0
     30      0      0      0      2
     36      0      0      1      1
     42      0      0      2      0
     48      0      0      3      6
     63      1      0      3      0
     72      0      0      2      2
     78      0      0      3      1
     91      1      1      1      0
    120      0      0      0      1
    240      0      0      0      2

  Notable patterns:
  All h(E_n) ‚â° 0 mod h(G2)=6: h(E6)=12, h(E7)=18, h(E8)=30
    12 mod 6 = 0, 18 mod 6 = 0, 30 mod 6 = 0 ‚úì

  |BI| mod H_forb_1 = 120 mod 7 = 1 = 1 (unit!)
  |BT| mod H_forb_1 = 24 mod 7 = 3 = KEY2!
  |BO| mod H_forb_1 = 48 mod 7 = 6 = h(G2)!
  |Phi(E8)| mod H_forb_1 = 240 mod 7 = 2 = KEY2!

  CROWN JEWEL: |BI| ‚â° 1 (mod H_forb_1)!
  120 = 17 * 7 + 1. So |BI| leaves remainder 1 when divided by H_forb_1.

  This means: in Z/7Z, |BI| = 1 = the identity!
  The icosahedral group order is TRIVIAL modulo the first forbidden number!

Special modular relationships:
  |BT| mod KEY_SUM = 4 = KEY1^2
  |BO| mod KEY_SUM = 3 = KEY2
  |BI| mod KEY_SUM = 0 = 0 (divisible!)
  |BI| mod KEY2 = 0 = 0 (divisible!)
  |BI| mod KEY1 = 0 = 0 (divisible!)
  |BI| mod H_forb_1 = 1 = 1 (unit!)
  |BI| mod 11 = 10 = 10
  |BI| = 2! * 3! * 5! / (2! * 3!) = KEY_SUM! = 120
  Actually: |BI| = KEY_SUM! = 5! = 120

  |BT| = (KEY1*KEY2)! / KEY1! = 4!/2 = 24/... no.
  |BT| = KEY1^3 * KEY2 = 8*3 = 24 = 4! = (KEY1^2)!
  |BO| = KEY1^4 * KEY2 = 16*3 = 48 = 2*|BT| = KEY1 * |BT|
  |BI| = KEY1^3 * KEY2 * KEY_SUM = 120 = KEY_SUM!

  FACTORIAL STRUCTURE:
  |BT| = (KEY1^2)! = 4! = 24
  |BI| = KEY_SUM! = 5! = 120
  h(G2) = KEY2! = 3! = 6

  So: h(G2) = KEY2!, |BT| = (KEY1^2)!, |BI| = KEY_SUM!

  But |BO| = 48 is NOT a factorial.
  48 = 2 * 24 = KEY1 * |BT| = KEY1 * (KEY1^2)!

======================================================================
  Part 10: THE (2,3,5,7) PRIME CONSTELLATION
======================================================================

The tournament primes {2, 3, 5, 7} form a remarkable constellation:

  Gaps: 3-2=1, 5-3=2=KEY1, 7-5=2=KEY1
  Product: 2*3*5*7 = 210 = primorial(7)/1
  Sum: 2+3+5+7 = 17 (prime!)

  210 = 2*3*5*7 = KEY1*KEY2*KEY_SUM*H_forb_1

  Product: 210 = 2 * 3 * 5 * 7
  Sum: 17 (prime)
  Sum of squares: 87 = 87
    = 3 * 29
  Sum of cubes: 503 = 503
    = 503

  210 = 2*3*5*7:
  210 = T_20 (20th triangular number!)
    T_20 = 20*21/2 = 210
    20 = 4*KEY_SUM, 21 = H_forb_2
  210 = C(21,2)/... no. 210 = C(10,4) = C(V(Pet), KEY1^2)
  Actually: C(10,4) = 210 = 210 ‚úì
  So 210 = C(V(Pet), KEY1^2) = KEY1*KEY2*KEY_SUM*H_forb_1!
  Also: 210 = C(21,2)/... 21*20/2 = 210 = C(H_forb_2, KEY1)/1

  17 = sum of tournament primes = KEY1+KEY2+KEY_SUM+H_forb_1
  17 is the 7th prime = the H_forb_1-th prime!
  17 appears in: Cat(E6) = 833 = 7^2 * 17 = H_forb_1^2 * 17
  and: Leech/E8 ratio decomposition uses 13, 17 nearby

  Partitions of 17: p(17) = 297 = 3^3 * 11
  297 = 3^3 * 11 = KEY2^3 * 11
  = 27 * 11 (27 lines on cubic times 11)

  CROWN JEWEL: 210 = C(V(Pet), KEY1^2) = T_20 = KEY1*KEY2*KEY_SUM*H_forb_1
  The product of all tournament primes = a binomial coefficient of V(Pet)!
  And also the 20th triangular number (where 20 = 4*KEY_SUM).

======================================================================
  Part 11: THE PARTITION FUNCTION AND (2,3)
======================================================================

The partition function p(n) counts ways to write n as a sum of positive integers.
Hardy-Ramanujan: p(n) ~ exp(pi*sqrt(2n/3)) / (4n*sqrt(3))

The formula involves sqrt(2/3) = sqrt(KEY1/KEY2)!

Also: the exponent pi*sqrt(2n/3) = pi*sqrt(KEY1*n/KEY2)

Ramanujan congruences for p(n):
  p(5k+4) ‚â° 0 (mod 5)    ‚Äî mod KEY_SUM
  p(7k+5) ‚â° 0 (mod 7)    ‚Äî mod H_forb_1
  p(11k+6) ‚â° 0 (mod 11)  ‚Äî mod 11

  The first two congruence moduli are KEY_SUM and H_forb_1!

Partition function at tournament numbers:
  p(KEY1     =   2) =          2 = 2   = KEY1!
  p(KEY2     =   3) =          3 = 3   = KEY2!
  p(KEY_SUM  =   5) =          7 = 7   = H_forb_1!
  p(h(G2)    =   6) =         11 = 11  
  p(H_forb_1 =   7) =         15 = 3 * 5  
  p(V(Pet)   =  10) =         42 = 2 * 3 * 7  
  p(h(E6)    =  12) =         77 = 7 * 11  
  p(|BT|     =  24) =       1575 = 3^2 * 5^2 * 7  
  p(h(E8)    =  30) =       5604 = 2^2 * 3 * 467  

  p(KEY1) = 2 = KEY1  (self-referential!)
  p(KEY2) = 3 = KEY2  (SELF-REFERENTIAL! p(3) = 3!)
  p(KEY_SUM) = 7 = H_forb_1!

  CROWN JEWEL: p(KEY_SUM) = H_forb_1 = 7!
  The number of partitions of KEY_SUM IS the first forbidden value!

  p(2) = KEY1, p(3) = KEY2, p(5) = H_forb_1
  The partition function maps tournament constants to tournament constants!

  Also: p(KEY1) = KEY1, p(KEY2) = KEY2 ‚Äî fixed points!
  But p(KEY_SUM) = H_forb_1 ‚âÝ KEY_SUM ‚Äî it "jumps" to the forbidden value!

  p(h(E6)) = 77 = 7 * 11
  p(|BT|) = 1575 = 3^2 * 5^2 * 7

======================================================================
  Part 12: PENTAGONAL NUMBER THEOREM AND (2,3)
======================================================================

Euler's pentagonal number theorem:
  prod_{n>=1} (1 - q^n) = sum_k (-1)^k q^{k(3k-1)/2}

The exponents k(3k-1)/2 are the GENERALIZED PENTAGONAL NUMBERS:
  k=1: 1*(3-1)/2 = 1
  k=-1: -1*(-4)/2 = 2
  k=2: 2*(6-1)/2 = 5 = KEY_SUM!
  k=-2: -2*(-7)/2 = 7 = H_forb_1!!
  k=3: 3*(9-1)/2 = 12 = h(E6)!
  k=-3: -3*(-10)/2 = 15 = C(6,2)
  k=4: 4*(12-1)/2 = 22
  k=-4: -4*(-13)/2 = 26
  k=5: 5*(15-1)/2 = 35
  k=-5: -5*(-16)/2 = 40

  CROWN JEWEL: The generalized pentagonal numbers include:
  1, 2, 5, 7, 12, 15, 22, 26, 35, 40, 51, 57, ...

  The FIRST FOUR are 1, KEY1, KEY_SUM, H_forb_1!
  The FIFTH is h(E6) = 12!

  These are exactly the exponents in the Euler product for eta(tau)!
  eta(tau) = q^{1/24} prod (1-q^n) where 1/24 = 1/|BT|

  The eta function involves both |BT| (as 1/24 prefactor)
  and the pentagonal numbers {1, KEY1, KEY_SUM, H_forb_1, h(E6), ...}!

Generalized pentagonal numbers and tournament vocabulary:
    1. GP_1 =    1  unit
    2. GP_2 =    2  KEY1
    3. GP_3 =    5  KEY_SUM!
    4. GP_4 =    7  H_forb_1!!
    5. GP_5 =   12  h(E6)!
    6. GP_6 =   15  C(6,2)
    7. GP_7 =   22  C(12,2)/... 2*11
    8. GP_8 =   26  2*13
    9. GP_9 =   35  5*7 = KEY_SUM * H_forb_1
   10. GP_10 =   40  8*5
   11. GP_11 =   51  3*17
   12. GP_12 =   57  3*19
   13. GP_13 =   70  CANNONBALL! = V(Pet)*H_forb_1
   14. GP_14 =   77  7*11
   15. GP_15 =   92  4*23
   16. GP_16 =  100  
   17. GP_17 =  117  
   18. GP_18 =  126  
   19. GP_19 =  145  
   20. GP_20 =  155  

  STUNNING: The pentagonal numbers contain BOTH KEY_SUM=5 AND H_forb_1=7!
  They are consecutive pentagonal numbers (for k=2 and k=-2)!

  Also: GP = 35 = KEY_SUM * H_forb_1 (the product of the two "special" values)
  And: GP = 70 = V(Pet) * H_forb_1 = the CANNONBALL number!

======================================================================
  Part 13: THE DEDEKIND ETA AND TOURNAMENT MODULAR FORMS
======================================================================

The Dedekind eta function:
  eta(tau) = q^{1/24} * prod_{n=1}^inf (1 - q^n)

  where q = e^{2*pi*i*tau}

The power 1/24 = 1/|BT| is the MOST IMPORTANT constant in modular forms!

The modular discriminant:
  Delta(tau) = eta(tau)^{24} = eta(tau)^{|BT|}

  So Delta = (eta)^{|BT|}: the discriminant is the |BT|-th power of eta!

eta transformations:
  eta(tau + 1) = e^{pi*i/12} * eta(tau)  ‚Äî involves 1/12 = 1/h(E6)!
  eta(-1/tau) = sqrt(-i*tau) * eta(tau)  ‚Äî involves sqrt, the KEY1-th root

  The 24th root of unity e^{2*pi*i/24} = e^{pi*i/12}
  So eta(tau+1)/eta(tau) = e^{pi*i/h(E6)}

  Under SL(2,Z) = <S, T | S^2 = (ST)^3 = -I>:
  eta transforms with a multiplier system involving 24th roots of unity.
  24 = |BT|: the eta multiplier system lives in Z/|BT|Z!

Powers of eta and their modular weights:
  eta^ 1: weight  1/2  Dedekind eta itself
  eta^ 2: weight    1  weight 1 form
  eta^ 3: weight  3/2  weight 3/2 (half-integer!)
  eta^ 4: weight    2  theta-like
  eta^ 6: weight    3  h(G2)-th power
  eta^ 8: weight    4  weight KEY1^2
  eta^12: weight    6  h(E6)-th power, weight h(G2)
  eta^24: weight   12  Delta = eta^|BT|, weight h(E6)

  eta^24 = Delta has weight 12 = h(E6)!
  eta^12 has weight h(G2) = 6
  eta^6 has weight KEY2 = 3

  The hierarchy: eta ‚Üí eta^h(G2) ‚Üí eta^h(E6) ‚Üí eta^|BT| = Delta
  Weights:       1/2 ‚Üí    KEY2    ‚Üí   h(G2)   ‚Üí  h(E6)

  Each step multiplies the exponent by KEY1 or KEY2:
  1 ‚Üí 6 = 1*h(G2) [√ó6]
  6 ‚Üí 12 = 6*KEY1 [√óKEY1]
  12 ‚Üí 24 = 12*KEY1 [√óKEY1]

  The eta exponent ladder: 1, h(G2), h(E6), |BT|
  = 1, 6, 12, 24 = 1, 2*3, 4*3, 8*3
  = KEY2 * (0.3333333333333333, 2, 4, 8) ... or = KEY2 * KEY1^(-1, 1, 2, 3) * something

  Actually: 1, 6, 12, 24 = |W(trivial)|, |W(A2)|, |W(G2)|, |W(A3)|
  These are Weyl group orders!

======================================================================
  Part 14: LANGLANDS DUAL AND (2,3)
======================================================================

The Langlands program connects:
  - Automorphic forms on G(A) (adelic points of algebraic group G)
  - Galois representations of Gal(Q_bar/Q) into G^L (Langlands dual)

For G = GL(2): G^L = GL(2) (self-dual!)
For G = GL(3): G^L = GL(3) (self-dual!)

The relevant L-functions:
  L(s, pi) for an automorphic representation pi of GL(n)

For GL(2), the classical modular forms give:
  L(s, f) = sum a_n * n^{-s}

For the Ramanujan Delta function (weight 12 = h(E6)):
  L(s, Delta) = sum tau(n) * n^{-s}

  Functional equation: Lambda(s) = Lambda(12-s) = Lambda(h(E6)-s)
  The center of symmetry is at s = h(E6)/2 = h(G2)!

  Critical strip: 0 < Re(s) < h(E6)
  Critical line: Re(s) = h(G2)
  Critical values: L(Delta, k) for k = 1, 2, ..., 11

For the Riemann zeta (GL(1)):
  Functional equation: Lambda(s) = Lambda(1-s)
  Center: s = 1/2 = 1/KEY1

The HIERARCHY:
  GL(1): center at 1/KEY1
  GL(2), weight h(E6): center at h(G2)
  GL(2), weight k: center at k/2

  The critical line moves from 1/KEY1 (GL1) to h(G2) (GL2 weight h(E6)).

Critical values and functional equations:
  Riemann zeta: center s = 1/2
  Delta L-function: center s = 12/2 = h(G2) = 6
  Weight 2 newforms: center s = 2/2 = 1
  Weight 4 (Eisenstein E4): center s = 4/2 = KEY1
  Weight 6 (Eisenstein E6): center s = 6/2 = KEY2
  Weight 10 (Eisenstein E10): center s = 10/2 = KEY_SUM
  Weight 14: center s = 14/2 = H_forb_1

  The center of symmetry = weight/KEY1
  So weight = 2*center:
  center = KEY2 ‚Üí weight = h(G2)
  center = h(G2) ‚Üí weight = h(E6)
  center = h(E6) ‚Üí weight = |BT|

  CROWN JEWEL: The Langlands functional equation centers form the sequence
  1/KEY1, 1, KEY1, KEY2, KEY_SUM, h(G2), H_forb_1, ...
  corresponding to modular forms of weights
  1, KEY1, KEY1^2, h(G2), V(Pet), h(E6), dim(G2), ...

  The MODULAR WEIGHT LADDER is the (2,3) universe!

